  "success": true,
  "output": "## Performance Analysis\n\nThis is a Python asyncio/SQLite job-scraping pipeline, not a web frontend — there's no React here, so I've mapped that category to its closest analog (redundant per-item recomputation in a hot loop). Findings below are ranked by impact.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-97` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job returned by a fetch run (Amazon/Microsoft/Netflix boards alone can be several thousand postings), the code does **one `SELECT` + one `INSERT`/`UPDATE`**, each a separate round-trip to sqlite, in a Python loop:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    ...\n```\n\nFor 5,000 jobs that's 10,000+ individual `cursor.execute()` calls. Fix: load all existing `(key, content_hash)` pairs once, diff in Python, then batch-write with `executemany`:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = dict(self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\"))\n\n    new, changed, seen_unchanged = [], [], []\n    insert_rows, update_rows = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        row = {**job.to_row(), \"now\": now}\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); insert_rows.append(row)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); update_rows.append(row)\n        else:\n            seen_unchanged.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if insert_rows:\n        self.conn.executemany(_INSERT_SQL, insert_rows)\n    if update_rows:\n        self.conn.executemany(_UPDATE_SQL, update_rows)\n    if seen_unchanged:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", seen_unchanged)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(2N) round-trips into 4 statements total.\n\n### 2. Redundant regex recompilation in the filter hot loop — `filters.py:11-41`\n\n`match()` is called once per job, and it calls `_compile(exclude)` and `_compile(include)` **inside that per-job call** — recompiling the same keyword regexes from scratch for every single job in the batch:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every call\n```\n\nFix: compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include_re, exclude_re, rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff)]\n```\n\nCheap for a handful of keywords, but scales linearly with both keyword count and job count — for a run across 15 sources with many include/exclude terms this is thousands of needless `re.compile()` calls.\n\n### 3. Redundant computation: `content_hash` recomputed multiple times, and `asdict()` deep-copies `raw` just to discard it — `models.py:66-75`\n\n`content_hash` is a plain `@property` (sha256 over 4 strings), recomputed every time it's accessed. In the `diff()` path it's computed once for the comparison (`job.content_hash`) and again inside `to_row()` during insert/update — 2x per job, 3x if you also touch it in `notify_webhook`.\n\nBigger issue: `to_row()` calls `dataclasses.asdict(self)`, which **deep-copies every field including `raw`** (which holds the full upstream JSON payload for Meta/Amazon/Microsoft/etc.) before popping `raw` off the result:\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)   # deep-copies `raw` (potentially large nested dict) for nothing\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)\n    ...\n```\n\nFix — build the row dict directly instead of going through `asdict`, and cache the hash:\n\n```python\nfrom functools import cached_property  # needs a dict slot, see note below\n\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    return {\n        \"source\": self.source, \"company\": self.company, \"external_id\": self.external_id,\n        \"title\": self.title, \"url\": self.url, \"location\": self.location,\n        \"department\": self.department, \"employment_type\": self.employment_type,\n        \"posted_at\": self.posted_at, \"salary_range\": self.salary_range,\n        \"key\": self.key, \"content_hash\": self.content_hash,\n    }\n```\n\nSince `Job` uses `slots=True`, `functools.cached_property` needs an explicit `__slots__` entry (or just a private `_content_hash` field set lazily) to cache the hash across the ~2-3 accesses per job per run.\n\n### 4. Caching opportunity: no conditional HTTP requests — `fetchers.py`\n\nEvery scheduled run (per the 12h cron in the recent commit) re-fetches entire boards from scratch — Microsoft/Amazon/Netflix paginate 30-40 pages each, every single run, even though most pages are unchanged between runs. None of the fetchers send `If-None-Match`/`If-Modified-Since`, and `httpx.AsyncClient` isn't reusing a cache. Since the whole point of the pipeline is diffing against previous state, adding a simple per-URL ETag cache (store `etag` alongside `meta` in `store.py`, pass `headers={\"If-None-Match\": etag}` in `_request`, treat 304 as \"reuse last payload\") would cut most of the outbound request volume on unpaged/simple endpoints (Greenhouse, Lever, Ashby, etc. — the `_simple` fetchers) where the board didn't change.\n\n### 5. Sequential pagination where concurrency is possible — `fetch_workday` (`fetchers.py:422-470`)\n\nWorkday's response includes `total` after the *first* page, but subsequent pages are still fetched one at a time in a `while True` loop with an `await` each iteration. Once `total` is known, the remaining `offset` values could be fetched concurrently (bounded by the existing semaphore) instead of serially:\n\n```python\nfirst = await _get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\", json={..., \"offset\": 0}, ...)\ntotal = first.get(\"total\", 0)\noffsets = range(page_size, min(total, 5000), page_size)\nrest = await asyncio.gather(*(_get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\",\n                                          json={..., \"offset\": o}, ...) for o in offsets))\n```\nThis turns O(total/page_size) sequential round-trips into one wave of concurrent ones (still gated by the fetch-level semaphore in `fetch_all`). The other bespoke paginators (`fetch_google`, `fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_optiver`) can't do this because they only know to stop when a page returns nothing new — that part is correctly sequential.\n\n### Memory leaks / unbounded growth\nNo real leaks — this is a short-lived CLI process (`asyncio.run(...)` then exit), so nothing outlives the run. The one thing worth flagging: `fetch_all` gathers **every** job (with its full `raw` payload) from **every** source into one list in memory before filtering (`pipeline.py:30-33`). For a config with many large boards this means holding thousands of full upstream JSON payloads simultaneously just to discard most of `raw` a few lines later in `to_row()`. If memory becomes a real constraint, the `raw` field could be dropped right after parsing (or made `Optional`/lazy) instead of carried through the whole pipeline.\n\n### Priority order\n1. **`Store.diff` batching** (#1) — biggest win, straightforward, no behavior change.\n2. **Regex compile hoist in filters** (#2) — trivial fix, real waste on multi-keyword configs.\n3. **`to_row`/`asdict` avoidance** (#3) — removes needless deep-copies of large payloads.\n4. HTTP conditional caching (#4) and Workday concurrent pagination (#5) are valuable but touch network/cache-invalidation logic — worth doing as a follow-up rather than bundled with the above.\n",
